    <h2 id="anchor1">What is this prototype?</h2>
    <p>This prototype is part of a govCMS theme and exists as a playground for developing pages and layouts based on the UI-kit.</p>
    <p>The package contains:
      <ul>
        <li>This prototype with associated tooling; and</li>
        <li>An associated govCMS theme with similar tooling</li>
      </ul>
      </p>

    <h2 id="anchor2">How to use it</h2>
    <p>The theme/prototype package can be used to suit your workflow. however, a proposed workflow is: 
      <ol>
        <li>Install it as a theme within govCMS</li>
        <li>Reference the <a href="https://gov-au-ui-kit.apps.staging.digital.gov.au">DTA Design Guide &amp; UI-kit</a> to discover the building blocks for prototyping.</li>
        <li>Build, test and deploy prototypes within /uikit_base/build</li>
        <li>Build, test and deploy the base theme within /uikit_base/*</li>
        <li>Create a sub-theme</li>
      </ol>
    </p>

    <h2 id="anchor3">Base theme vs sub-theme</h2>
    <p>The theme/prototype base theme uses only the UI-kit.</p>
    <p>To create custom themes/prototypes you should create a sub-theme. This is seperate from the base theme and inherits the UI-kit (which supports easy updates).</p>
    <p>More information about the sub-theme development is available in <strong>README-FIRST.txt</strong> in the theme root.</p>

    <h2 id="anchor4">Boilerplate</h2>
    <p>The UI-kit is not prescriptive with respect to boilerplating but instead provides modular components to permit easy site building.</p>
    <p>For example, <a href="content.html">alternative content page</a> includes a larger global header and a smaller hero block.</p>
  </article>
